#This problem has been slightly simplified and converted to just asking for b, #a, r, and k.

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
#           "parserPopUp.pl"
"MathObjects.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
           );

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");
Context()->flags->set(useBaseTenLog=>1);

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(150,250,10);
$b = random(1.201,1.999,0.001);

$r = ($b-1);
#$k = ln($b);

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Give the growth factor \(b\), the starting value \(a\), the growth rate \(r\), and the value of \(k\) when \(Q\) is written in the form \(Q = ae^{kt}\). If there is exponential is decay, then your growth rate should negative.
For help entering logarithms, see \{ AnswerFormatHelp("logarithms") \}
$PAR
\( Q = $a \cdot ($b)^t \) has:
$PAR
\( b = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( a = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( r = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( k = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS( Real("$b")->cmp() );
ANS( Real("$a")->cmp() );
ANS( Real("$r")->cmp() );
ANS( Compute("ln($b)")->cmp() );

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR
This is written as \(Q=$a\cdot($b)^t\),
so that
\(a=$a\),
\(b=$b\),
\(r=b-1=$r\), and
\(k=\ln b=\ln $b\).

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

COMMENT('MathObject version.  Uses log = logten');
ENDDOCUMENT();
